The data set I selected for this project is the COVID-19 Vaccination data set from the World Health Organization (WHO), which compiles information originally collected through the University of Maryland Global COVID-19 Trends and Impact Survey (UMD-CTIS) in partnership with Facebook. This global survey was conducted from April 23, 2020, to June 25, 2022, with the final data set released in April 2023. The UMD-CTIS collected data on a range of topics including burden, mental health, beliefs and behaviors, financial worry, information, testing, and vaccine coverage and hesitancy.The data are disaggreated by age, gender, education, health worker status, and place of residence. I figure this data is useful in finding out inequalities in vaccine access and uptake across populations.

Main Question: Is COVID-19 vaccine associated with education level across different countries?

The data set contains 301,032 observations (rows) and 24 variables (columns). There are three types of variables character, numeric and one logical. Some variables Irrelevant data variables for my question of interest are the month/year when the estimate was generated, flag, ordered_dimension, reference, subgroup, dataset_id, indicator scale, and update. Population seems a bit suspicious with the max population being 13 billion. According to online search, China has a the highest population in 2022 with 1.41 billion. Looking at the top 10 largest population, India has many population observations above 14 billion, this might be data setâs calculation for population. I looked at the metadata, and it says that the âpopulationâ column in the WHO/UMD-CTIS dataset represents the weighted survey representation size rather than the true census population.

One important variable is estimate (which is tells about the % of vaccinated, % of vaccinated, % of who is hesitate to get vaccine due to cost, etc). Other important variables are subgroup and dimension. Age is categorized into four unique groups (18â24 years, 25â44 years, 45â64 years, and 65+ years). Education appears in two forms, depending on the survey period: one version divides respondents by education level into four subgroups (less than secondary education, secondary education, four-year degree, and postgraduate education), while the other measures years of schooling completed with five subgroups (no education, 1â6 years, 7â12 years, 13â15 years, and 16â30 years). Gender includes two subgroups, male and female. Place of residence distinguishes between urban and rural based on self-reported.

#Visualize the disturbution of key variables

library(ggplot2)
library(stringr)
library(forcats)
data_clean <- data %>%
  filter(!is.na(estimate), estimate >= 0, estimate <= 100) %>%
  #mutate(new_column = some_transformation(old_column))
  mutate(indicator_short = str_wrap(indicator_name, width = 35)) #create new column "indicator_short"
ggplot(data_clean, aes(x = estimate)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "white") +
  labs(title = "Overall Distribution of Estimates",
       x = "Estimate (%)", y = "Count")
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value `binwidth`.
ggplot(data_clean,
       aes(y = fct_reorder(indicator_short, estimate, .fun = median), #reorder by median
           x = estimate)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.3, fill = "grey") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Estimates Across Indicators",
       x = "Estimate (%)", y = "Indicator") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 11) +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = 8))
 vaccine_edu <- data_clean %>%
  filter(
    indicator_name %in% c("Self-reported receipt of a COVID-19 vaccine (%)",
                          "Received two doses of the COVID-19 vaccine (%)"),
    grepl("Education", dimension, ignore.case = TRUE), #include
    !grepl("barrier", indicator_name, ignore.case = TRUE)  # remove vaccine barrier 
  ) %>%
  mutate(subgroup = fct_reorder(subgroup, estimate))

ggplot(vaccine_edu, aes(x = subgroup, y = estimate)) +
  geom_violin(fill = "skyblue", color = "black", alpha = 0.4) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Self-Reported COVID-19 Vaccine Uptake by Education Subgroup",
    subtitle = "Excluding all 'Vaccination barrier' indicators",
    x = "Education subgroup",
    y = "Vaccination (%)"
  )

We see a right skewed distribution for estimate, so I use median to reorder the data. From the indicator short (indicator name), we can see that there are still many people choose to getting two doses of vaccine or self reported getting COVID-19 vaccine. Then we address my primary question I made a violin plot between estimate of self-reported receipt of a COVID-19 vaccine (%) and received two doses of the COVID-19 vaccine (%) as my group of being vaccinated and plot is against education subgroup. From this plot, it indicates a positive association between education level and vaccination uptake. Participants with higher education show higher vaccination rates, and this could due to increased knowledge of public health, awareness of disease prevention strategies, and knowledge in how vaccine works. After finding out the answer for my primary question, I now what to know is getting vaccine related to health worker status, age and income level.

#Future question â What is the relationship between health worker status, age, place of residence, and income level with vaccine status?

#Age VS Vaccine status
Age <- data_clean %>%
  filter(
    indicator_name %in% c("Self-reported receipt of a COVID-19 vaccine (%)",
                          "Received two doses of the COVID-19 vaccine (%)"),
    grepl("Age", dimension, ignore.case = TRUE), #include
    !grepl("barrier", indicator_name, ignore.case = TRUE)  # remove vaccine barrier 
  ) %>%
  mutate(subgroup = fct_reorder(subgroup, estimate)) 

ggplot(Age, aes(x = subgroup, y = estimate)) +
  geom_violin(fill = "skyblue", color = "black", alpha = 0.4) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Self-Reported COVID-19 Vaccine Uptake by Age Subgroup",
    subtitle = "Excluding all 'Vaccination barrier' indicators",
    x = "Age subgroup",
    y = "Vaccination (%)"
  )
#Health worker status VS Vaccine status
Health <- data_clean %>%
  filter(
    indicator_name %in% c("Self-reported receipt of a COVID-19 vaccine (%)",
                          "Received two doses of the COVID-19 vaccine (%)"),
    grepl("Health worker", dimension, ignore.case = TRUE), #include
    !grepl("barrier", indicator_name, ignore.case = TRUE)  # remove vaccine barrier 
  ) %>%
  mutate(subgroup = fct_reorder(subgroup, estimate))

ggplot(Health, aes(x = subgroup, y = estimate)) +
  geom_violin(fill = "skyblue", color = "black", alpha = 0.4) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Self-Reported COVID-19 Vaccine Uptake by Health Worker Status Subgroup",
    subtitle = "Excluding all 'Vaccination barrier' indicators",
    x = "Health Worker Status subgroup",
    y = "Vaccination (%)"
  ) 
#place of residence Vs vaccine status 
place <- data_clean %>%
  filter(
    indicator_name %in% c("Self-reported receipt of a COVID-19 vaccine (%)",
                          "Received two doses of the COVID-19 vaccine (%)"),
    grepl("resident", dimension, ignore.case = TRUE)|
      grepl("urban|rural", subgroup, ignore.case = TRUE),
    !grepl("barrier", indicator_name, ignore.case = TRUE)  # remove vaccine barrier 
  ) %>%
  mutate(subgroup = fct_reorder(subgroup, estimate))

ggplot(place, aes(x = subgroup, y = estimate)) +
  geom_violin(fill = "skyblue", color = "black", alpha = 0.4) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Self-Reported COVID-19 Vaccine Uptake by Place of Residence Subgroup",
    subtitle = "Excluding all 'Vaccination barrier' indicators",
    x = "Place of Residence subgroup",
    y = "Vaccination (%)"
  )
# Income Vs Vaccine status 
income <- data_clean %>%
  filter(
    indicator_name %in% c(
      "Self-reported receipt of a COVID-19 vaccine (%)",
      "Received two doses of the COVID-19 vaccine (%)"
    ),
    !grepl("barrier", indicator_name, ignore.case = TRUE),
    !is.na(wbincome2023)
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    wbincome2023 = fct_relevel(  #sets the order of those factor levels manually
      as.factor(wbincome2023), #convert to factor (catergorical variable)
      "Low income",
      "Lower middle income",
      "Upper middle income",
      "High income"
    )
  )

ggplot(income, aes(x = wbincome2023, y = estimate)) +
  geom_violin(fill = "skyblue", color = "black", alpha = 0.4, trim = FALSE) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Self-Reported COVID-19 Vaccine Uptake by Country Income Level (2023)",
    subtitle = "Excluding all 'Vaccination barrier' indicators",
    x = "World Bank Income Group (2023)",
    y = "Vaccination (%)"
  )

We can see that older individuals tend to have higher vaccination rates. This pattern is expected, as older adults are more likely to have underlying health conditions that could lead to severe or even fatal outcomes if they become infected. The elderly population is also the group most often prioritized for vaccination campaigns.Among younger age groups, vaccination rates appear to be relatively even, showing no strong differences in uptake.

Health workers have higher vaccination rates compared with nonâhealth workers, which makes sense given their greater exposure to infectious diseases and the need to protect both themselves and their patients.When comparing place of residence, vaccination percentages are similar between rural and urban areas, suggesting limited disparity based on location. However, income level shows a clearer pattern: high-income countries have a greater tendency toward vaccination than lower-income countries. The upper-middle-income and lower-middle-income groups show similar patterns, though the upper-middle-income group demonstrates a slightly stronger tendency to be vaccinated.
